  "sourceType": "CLASSIC",
  "sourceNotes": "Apple pie in various forms appears in American domestic cookery from the colonial period, drawing on British and Dutch traditions. Fannie Farmer, The Boston Cooking-School Cook Book (1896), gives an apple pie recipe using a standard shortcrust; the double-crust form became the American standard through the nineteenth century. The use of cinnamon and nutmeg as the primary spicing, and the deep-dish form in a sloping-sided tin, are American developments distinct from the British double-crust pie.",
